    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-07-16_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth Town</placeName> <note>56</note>
                        <date when="1811-07-16"> July 16 <hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date></dateline> 
                    
                  My Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName></opener>
                <p> 
                    
                  The beginning of your letter of<lb/>
                  the 4<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. was illusive - I expected every moment<lb/>
                  to hear that you had fixed a time for<lb/>
                  coming here. - You put your nephew<lb/>
                  forward as an excuse for <hi rend="underline">not keeping</hi> I<lb/>
                  wont say for <hi rend="underline">breaking your promise</hi> -<lb/>
                  but you tell us in the same page that<lb/>
                  you are at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Holland-House_ENK">Holland-house.</placeName> ! ! !<lb/></p>
                  <p>
                  Now I know of nothing more <unclear>can</unclear><lb/>
                  than disposing of your nephew by<lb/>
                  bringing him along with - or nothing<lb/>
                  more difficult than leaving <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxE1">Lady Holland</persName><lb/></p>
                  <p>
                  I now plainly perceive that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName><lb/>
                  did not go far enough in "To morrow"<lb/>
                  Or that she should write for some <unclear>folk</unclear><lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">The day after tomorrow</hi> -<lb/></p>
                  <p>
                  I like the epigram on <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Bentham</persName><lb/>
                  exceedingly - I have not time to<lb/>
                  attempt the ease and <hi rend="underline">turn</hi> of the<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">original</hi> but I send you a prosaic<lb/>
                  translation that you may see my<lb/>
                  attention to you even in trifles<lb/></p>
                  <closer>
                  Yours truly<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lovell Edgeworth</persName><lb/></closer>
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-07-16_page02.jpg"/>
                <postscript>
              <p> <note>57</note>
                  Translation of Epigram on Farmer John<lb/>
                  Why tolls the bell? ? - T'is is farmer John<lb/>
                  at last the rich old soul is gone! -<lb/>
                  - Alas! he died not worth a groat<lb/>
                  He never sold &amp; always bought<lb/>
                  His farm was good, his stock was great<lb/>
                  Early at work, and working late -<lb/>
                  But here our farmer's merits stop<lb/>
                  He sowed, but scorned to reap the crop.<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">R.L.E.</persName><lb/></p>
                  <p>
                  My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> who has but just come home<lb/>
                  would not do any thing till he had <choice><orig>an-<lb/>
                  -swered</orig><reg>answered</reg></choice> your letter - he has given me his<lb/>
                  pen &amp; I use it to send you <add>for the second ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.</add><del>an epigram<lb/>
                  given to us ) on the Ed Rev of Professional</del><lb/>
                  of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Proff1">Prof. Education</title> - an epigram on the Ed Rev<hi rend="superscript">w</hi>. of that book<lb/>
                  S- S- who reviews by abusing &amp; lying<lb/>
                  Says this volume is worth neither borrowing nor <add>buying</add><lb/>
                  But the world buys the book &amp; finds out to his sorrow<lb/>
                  That he's eager to <hi rend="underline">steal</hi> what he scruples to <hi rend="underline">borrow</hi><lb/>
                      
                  <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-07-16_page03.jpg"/>
                  My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> much admires your plan of advice<lb/>
                  to a young man - <add>sur</add> des educations a refaire<lb/>
                  - He thinks it suited to the largeness of your<lb/>
                  views - but he says it cannot be comprised<lb/>
                  in a chapter in <title ref="./Workography.xml#Proff1">Professional Education.</title><lb/>
                  It must be a little work by itself which we are much<lb/>
                  inclined to attempt - </p><closer>Yours sincerely<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName> -<lb/></closer></postscript>
                  <closer> To<lb/>
                      <address>
                         <addrLine/>
                         <addrLine/>
                          <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">E. Dumont Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>.</persName>
                      </address>
                  </closer>
                
